First factor the denominator:  
\[
\frac{2x^4}{x^2-2x}
=\frac{2x^4}{x(x-2)}
=\frac{2x^3}{\,x-2\,}.
\]
Now divide \(2x^3\) by \(x-2\) by polynomial long‐division:

\[
\begin{array}{r|l}
x-2&2x^3+0x^2+0x+0\\\hline
&2x^2\quad+4x\quad+8\\
&(2x^3-4x^2)\\\cline{2-2}
&4x^2+0x\\
&(4x^2-8x)\\\cline{2-2}
&8x+0\\
&(8x-16)\\\cline{2-2}
&16
\end{array}
\]
So
\[
\frac{2x^3}{x-2}
=2x^2+4x+8+\frac{16}{\,x-2\,},
\]
and hence
\[
\frac{2x^4}{x^2-2x}
=\boxed{2x^2+4x+8\;+\;\frac{16}{\,x-2\,}}\,. 
\]
